Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and conditionally cancel it:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and hook into Shell's `Navigating` event for the shell back button:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating += OnShellNavigating;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating -= OnShellNavigating;
    }

    // Handles the Shell chrome back button / URI navigation
    private async void OnShellNavigating(object sender, ShellNavigatingEventArgs e)
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return;

        // Defer navigation so we can await the dialog
        var deferral = e.GetDeferral();

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave)
            e.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay"

        deferral.Complete();
    }

    // Handles Android/device hardware back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget because this override isn't async
        ConfirmBackNavigation();
        return true; // true = we handled it, suppress default behavior
    }

    private async void ConfirmBackNavigation()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;   // prevent re-trigger
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            IsVisible="True"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>

    <!-- or inline: -->
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `ShellNavigatingEventArgs.GetDeferral()` lets you `await` an async dialog before deciding to cancel.
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the Android hardware back — it's synchronous, so you return `true` immediately and navigate manually after the dialog.
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back-button tap, so your `Cancel` command gets full control.
